      "item": {
        "type": "markdown",
        "id": "387d4dbbdec27d6f",
        "text": "However, no institution wanted to implement the simple common sense inventions because the result was increased health, decreased expenditure. Also the key invention created a new role, the neighborhood health worker-- a non-degreed health support person. There continues to be much fighting over who controls this role, when it should be the neighborhoods themselves. The solution would have made practicing medicine much more emotionally rewarding and less frustrating. It would have saved Medicare billions of dollars. It was simple to understand and simple to implement. The profound disregard for this hard won innovation led me to shift my focus toward health creation and maintenance of health, to the so called \"social determinates of illness\" or better yet the neighborhood determinates of health. Working in the US medical industrial complex was not delivering on what the patients I met were asking for."
